Is there a good way to parse scientific notation in C/AFNI that I'm not aware of? I feel like that would be a big QOL boost for this feature, but I'm not really excited about trying to roll my own in C.

What do you mean about "parsing"? There are format specifiers in C, for reading and writing scientific notation.  %e and %g are useful ones for scientific notation:
Consider this C program, for displaying scientific notation:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main( void){
   float a = 100;
   float b = 1000000;

   printf("a as e:%e\n", a);   
   printf("a as f:%f\n", a);   
   printf("a as g:%g\n", a);   

   printf("b as e:%e\n", b);   
   printf("b as f:%f\n", b);   
   printf("b as g:%g\n", b);   

   return 0;
}

... which outputs:

a as e:1.000000e+02
a as f:100.000000
a as g:100
b as e:1.000000e+06
b as f:1000000.000000
b as g:1e+06

Note the difference is what 'g' does, depending on the value of the number.
Here is an example of reading in a text file of numbers, "file.txt":
1e5
2e-6
3e7

... and displaying them:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main( void){
   FILE *fff = fopen("file.txt", "r");
   float a, b, c;

   fscanf(fff, "%e", &a);
   fscanf(fff, "%e", &b);
   fscanf(fff, "%f", &c);

   printf("a as e:%e\n", a);   
   printf("a as f:%f\n", a);   
   printf("a as g:%g\n", a);   

   printf("b as e:%e\n", b);   
   printf("b as f:%f\n", b);   
   printf("b as g:%g\n", b);   

   printf("c as e:%e\n", c);   
   printf("c as f:%f\n", c);   
   printf("c as g:%g\n", c);   

   fclose(fff);

   return 0;
}

... which outputs:
a as e:1.000000e+05
a as f:100000.000000
a as g:100000
b as e:2.000000e-06
b as f:0.000002
b as g:2e-06
c as e:3.000000e+07
c as f:30000000.000000
c as g:3e+07

Note how even reading as %f worked as expected here.
Depending on the size of incoming number, one has to be careful about float/double/etc.

