@jbteves - I had some thoughts for the code, esp. on reading in the datasets initially.  I think that reading them in as THD_3dim_dataset types would be preferable to doing so as MRI_IMAGE types.  This should be more general, and allow for more standard flexibility of input naming, as well as verifying the consistency of multiple input dsets like for matching grids, etc.
In fact, this has inspired an update to 3dToyProg, or at least a separate kind of educational "starter" program with comments, with many inputs from @afni-rickr.  This is now in the code base: 3dEdu_01_scale.c (https://github.com/afni/afni/blob/master/src/3dEdu_01_scale.c).  I think this might be useful for tweaking the way inputs are done and reading in the data.  The output should be even simpler in your case with 3dDiff because you aren't outputting a dset, but instead numbers.
Please let us know how that seems.  (I expect we will make some more 3dEdu* progs, too, eventually.)

There is a function to check for dataset mismatches.  So, let's say you have 2 dsets, dset_A and dset_B.  The first thing I would do after loading them in would be to check :
// load in A and B
dset_A = THD_open_dataset(input_nameA);
if( (dset_A == NULL ))
   ERROR_exit("Can't open dataset '%s'", input_nameA);
DSET_load(dset_A); CHECK_LOAD_ERROR(dset_A);

dset_B = THD_open_dataset(input_nameB);
if( (dset_B == NULL ))
   ERROR_exit("Can't open dataset '%s'", input_nameB);
DSET_load(dset_B); CHECK_LOAD_ERROR(dset_B);

// check for mismatch
if( THD_dataset_mismatch( dset_A , dset_B ) ) {
   [output your message/output, whether in default/gentle or optional/brutal form]
   [delete/free dset_A and dset_B]
   [exit program in whatever fashion you are ending]
}

[... all the code to do the dataset testing/comparison that you want, because you survived the fireswamp of mismatched datasets]

In this way, your output should be simpler, rather than the current 8 numbers:
Brutalist output is useful for scripting. The output is an 8-integer 
array with the following elements:
	0:	Summary (-1 failure, 0 no difference, 1 some difference)
	1:	Dimensions (the number of differing dimensions)
	2:	Grid Spacing (0 if no difference, 1 if some)
	3:	Image Center (0 if no difference, 1 if some)
	4:	Obliquity (the angle of difference)
	5:	Orientation (0 if no difference, 1 if some)
	6:	Elements (total differing elements, -1 if cannot)
	7:	Total Elements (total elements compared, -1 if cannot)

... you can get rid of items 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.  So, you get the benefit of simpler reporting (only 3 numbers needed to output).  Basically, getting a "-1" as the first output can mean 'some kind of header difference---dear User, if you are unsure or surprised, prithee check "3dinfo -same_grid ..."' (or some other non-brutalist message).
If you add in a mask at some point, sure then that just would add a second comparison---check that dset_A and dset_B aren't mismatched, then check either of them with dset_mask.
--pt

OK, to fix the quiet "-q" output, I think the if condition there should look like:
    if ( quiet ) {
        printf("%d\n", ( total_elements_differing != 0 ));
    }

so that 1 is output if total_elements_differing does not equal zero, and 0 is output if total_elements_differing does equal zero.

